\f0\b \cf0 Docker\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa180\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 A description of the files related to Docker can be found in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#docker-files"}}{\fldrslt \ul Docker files}} section. To build the two Docker images, run the following commands from the root directory of the project.\
First, build the 'tools' image. This image contains a full Linux Swift toolchain and is capable of compiling your application for Linux:\
\pard\tx360\pardeftab720\li360\fi-360\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95	
\f2 docker build --tag myapp-build --file Dockerfile-tools .
\f1 \uc0\u8232 You may customize the names of these images by specifying a different value after the 
\f2 -t
\f1  option.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 To compile the application for Linux using the tools Docker image, run:\
\pard\tx360\pardeftab720\li360\fi-360\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95	
\f2 docker run --volume $PWD:/swift-project --workdir /swift-project myapp-build /swift-utils/tools-utils.sh build release
\f1 \uc0\u8232 This produces a 
\f2 .build-ubuntu
\f1  directory which will be incorporated into your final image.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Now that your application has been built, you can build the final run image:\
\pard\tx360\pardeftab720\li360\fi-360\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95	
\f2 docker build --tag myapp-run .
\f1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Finally, to run the application:\
\pard\tx360\pardeftab720\li360\fi-360\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95	
\f2 docker run -it --publish 8080:8080 myapp-run
\f1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa180\partightenfactor0

